=Description= [[File:twi_logo.png|thumb]] [https://www.wetlands-initiative.org/ The Wetlands Initiative website]
Envisioning a world with plentiful healthy wetlands improving water quality, climate, biodiversity, and human well-being. ==Vision== A world with plentiful healthy wetlands improving water quality, climate, biodiversity, and human well-being.
==Mission== The Wetlands Initiative designs, restores, and creates wetlands. We innovate, collaborate, and employ sound science to improve water quality, habitat for plants and wildlife, and our climate.
[[Category:Organization]][[Category:Non-Government]] {{#set: Has Organization=Audubon Great Lakes |Has Organization=Chicago Park District |Has Organization=The Field Museum }}

{{Organization Page}} =Description= [https://r2rbirds.org/ Road to Recovery website] [[File:r2r-logo.png|thumb]]
Road to Recovery ‚Ä¶is an independently funded enterprise focused on the recovery of the most rapidly declining birds in the United States and Canada. Our approach is a purposeful integration of biological and social science targeted at identifying and addressing specific causes of declines throughout the annual cycle. Starting with a set of Tipping Point species, R2R supports species-focused teams and projects. We work collectively with scientists, conservation practitioners, and local communities to create sustainable solutions for recovering bird populations.
[[Category:Organization]][[Category:Private]] {{#set: Has Organization=US NABCI |Has Organization=United States Fish and Wildlife Service |Has Organization=Golden-winged Warbler Working Group |Has Organization=Partners in Flight |Has Organization=Evening Grosbeak Working Group |Has Organization=Saltmarsh Habitat and Avian Research Program }}

{{Organization Page}} =Description= [https://www.tidalmarshbirds.org/ SHARP website] [[File:sharp-logo.png|thumb]]
With partners in governmental agencies, conservation non-profits, academic organizations, and private citizens, we support the science behind tidal marsh bird conservation. We answer the questions needed to prevent tidal marsh birds and their wetlands from vanishing.
