{{Plan Page}} In Development =Vision= To conserve, sustainably manage and restore forests and agroforestry systems at mid-elevations in Central and Northern South America in order to maintain and increase the non-breeding habitat of the Cerulean Warbler, Golden-winged Warbler and Canada Warbler, thus contributing to their conservation and the well-being of the social actors in the regions.
=Goal= Decrease the loss of forest habitats, increase the amount of habitat in degraded areas, maintain and/or increase the area covered by agroforestry systems, and halt the population declines of the three species ([[Golden-winged Warbler]], [[Cerulean Warbler]] and [[Canada Warbler]]) in the Plan's Action Area in Central America and Northern South America by 2031.
[[Category:Plan]] {{#set: Has Geography=Central America |Has Geography=South America |Has Organization=Partners in Flight |Has Organization=Partners in Flight Eastern Working Group |Has Organization=United States Fish and Wildlife Service |Has Organization=Audubon Panama |Has Organization=SELVA |Has Organization=Environment Canada |Has Species=Golden-winged Warbler |Has Species=Cerulean Warbler |Has Species=Canada Warbler }}

{{Plan Page}} In Development
=Executive Summary= Migratory landbirds breed in the northern hemisphere in Canada and the United States and migrate to Mexico, Central America and some as far as South America. They are among the most endangered species on the planet. A recent study determined that the United States and Canada have lost 3 billion birds since 1970. The Birds of Conservation Concern (BCC) list identifies 269 non-game migratory birds that, if no additional conservation measures are taken, may be species that enter the endangered species category. For resident birds that make use of these territories, the situation may be even worse. This steep decline in abundance can be reversed with new scales of conservation actions that benefit not only birds, but also wildlife and people.
[[Category:Plan]] {{#set: Has Geography=Central America |Has Geography=South America |Has Organization=Partners in Flight |Has Organization=Partners in Flight Eastern Working Group |Has Organization=Audubon Panama |Has Organization=BirdLife International |Has Organization=Environment Canada }}

{{Plan Page}}
==In Development==
=Executive Summary= The Choc√≥ bioregion and area of biodiversity endemism - shared between Ecuador and Colombia - totals about 100,000 km2 . Its conservation priority is critical due to habitat loss caused by certain human activities. In northwestern Ecuador, this area of approximately 18,542 km2 is known as the Choc√≥- Andes. It covers an altitudinal range from 0 to 3,800 meters above sea level and is home to unique bird species endemic to the Choc√≥ and the P√°ramos of the Central Andes, such as the endangered Ecuadorian endemic hummingbird, Zamarrito Pechinegro (Eriocnemis nigrivestis). It is also an important area for boreal migratory species such as the [[Cerulean Warbler]] (Setophaga cerulea).
[[Category:Plan]] {{#set: Has Geography=Ecuador |Has Geography=Colombia |Has Geography=South America |Has Organization=Partners in Flight |Has Organization=Partners in Flight Eastern Working Group |Has Organization=Aves y Conservaci√≥n |Has Organization=BirdLife International |Has Organization=Environment Canada |Has Organization=Fundaci√≥n Jocotoco |Has Species=Cerulean Warbler }}

